revision.text:
An '''alpha capture system''' is a computer system that enables [[investment bank]]s and other organisations to submit "trading ideas" or "[[trade idea]]s"<ref name="TIM Ideas">[http://www.timgroup.com/tim-ideas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929233308/http://www.timgroup.com/tim-ideas |date=2013-09-29 }} TIM Ideas</ref> to clients in a written electronic format, for example TIM Group's TIM Ideas product or Bloomberg LP's Trade Ideas product. Financial Services Authority Markets Division: Newsletter on Market Conduct and [[Transaction Reporting]] Issues, Issue No. 17, September 2006,<ref name="fsa">[http://www.fsa.gov.uk/pubs/newsletters/mw_newsletter17.pdf Market Watch], retrieved 8 January 2009</ref> First used in 2001 by [[Marshall Wace]]<ref name="FirstCoverage">[http://www.firstcoverage.com/documents/Wall%20Street%20Redefined.pdf Wall Street Redefined] by Bill Alpert, First Coverage, retrieved 8 January 2009</ref> they are an alternative to the traditional [[stockbroker]]ing approach of communicating ideas and strategies to clients face-to-face or over the telephone.<ref name="fsa" />

The term ''alpha capture'' refers to the aim of such systems to help investors find alpha or market-beating returns on investments.<ref name="FirstCoverage" /> Submitted trade ideas are accompanied by a rationale, timeframe and conviction level<ref name="fsa" /> and enable investors to quantify and monitor the performance of different ideas.<ref name="fsa" /><ref name="FirstCoverage" />

